'''USS ''Hartford'' (SSN-768)''', a {{sclass|Los Angeles|submarine}}, is the second ship of the Navy to be named for [[Hartford, Connecticut]]. The contract to build her was awarded to the [[Electric Boat]] Division of [[General Dynamics]] Corporation in [[Groton, Connecticut]] on 30&nbsp;June 1988 and her keel was laid down on 22&nbsp;February 1992. She was [[ship naming and launching|launched]] on 4&nbsp;December 1993 sponsored by Laura O'Keefe, wife of former [[Secretary of the Navy]] [[Sean O'Keefe]], and [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 10&nbsp;December 1994, with Commander George Kasten in command.

==In the news==
===2003 collision in Sardinia===
{{main|USS Hartford grounding}}
On 25 October 2003 [[USS Hartford grounding|''Hartford'' ran aground]] near [[La Maddalena]] in [[Sardinia]] with such force that rudders, sonar and other electronic equipment were severely damaged. After the accident Commander Christopher R. Van Metre, captain of Hartford, and Captain  Greg  Parker, Commodore of Submarine Squadron 22, were relieved of command and sent back to the United States. Six other crewmen were also charged with dereliction of duty.<ref> {{cite web 
|url=http://www.bellona.org/english_import_area/international/russia/nuke_industry/co-operation/31750
|title=Italy furious after US Navy tried to cover up sub accident
|author=Charles Digges
|date=2003-11-13
|accessdate=2008-08-31}}</ref>

===2009 collision in Strait of Hormuz===
{{main|USS Hartford and USS New Orleans collision}}
{{Wikinews|Two US Navy vessels collide in the Strait of Hormuz; 15 lightly injured}}On 20 March 2009 ''Hartford'' collided with [[amphibious transport dock]] {{USS|New Orleans|LPD-18}} in the [[Strait of Hormuz]], slightly injuring 15&nbsp;sailors on board. Both vessels were able to proceed under their own power after the incident, although the ''New Orleans'' suffered a ruptured fuel tank, releasing 25,000 gallons of diesel fuel into the strait<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cusnc.navy.mil/articles/2009/046.html |title=Two U.S. Navy Vessels Collide in the Strait of Hormuz |last=Commander |first=[[US Fifth Fleet]] |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-03-20}}</ref>

The Navy announced April 14, 2009 that the submarine's skipper, Commander Ryan Brookhart, had been relieved of duty by Rear Admiral Michael J. Connor because of a loss of confidence in Brookhart's ability to command.  Brookhart was replaced by Commander Chris Harkins, deputy commander of Submarine Squadron Eight.<ref>Clayton, Cindy, "Commander Of Sub That Collided With Ship Is Relieved Of Duty", ''[[Norfolk Virginian-Pilot]]'', April 15, 2009.</ref>

A repair contract has been awarded to [[General Dynamics]]. Repairs were initially expected to cost $37.4 million and be completed by January 2010.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 9, 2009|title=General Dynamics gets contract to repair submarine|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D99B26SG0.htm}}</ref> However, as of November 2009 repair costs had already exceeded $100 million. <ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC|date=19 November 2009|title='Complacency' led to US sub crash|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8367564.stm}}</ref>

